Brinker International announced its financial results for the second quarter ended Dec. 24, including an 8.6% increase in same-store sales for its flagship Chili’s brand.&nbsp;

The growth was primarily driven by higher traffic yet again, as well as menu enhancements, competitive pricing, ongoing advertising initiatives, and improved operations. Chili’s leveraged its higher sales to improve margins, while also repurchasing $100 million of the company’s stock.&nbsp;

Chili’s total sales for the second quarter were above $1.31 billion, compared to $1.2 billion in Q2 2025. Restaurant operating margin as a percentage of company sales was 19.1%, versus 18.7% in the same quarter last year.&nbsp;

"Chili's delivered another strong quarter with industry-leading growth of 9%, rolling the industry-leading growth from last year for a two-year comp sales growth of 43%," Brinker president and chief executive officer Kevin Hochman said in a statement. "With 19 consecutive quarters of same-store sales growth, Chili's turnaround, led by guest experience improvements, is sustaining over the long-term."

Hochman was brought on board in May 2022 to turn the chain’s performance around. The strategy he put into place, which focuses on investing back into the business for menu enhancements, operational simplification and execution, training, asset improvements, and more, has been nothing short of remarkable. Chili’s quarterly performance from the first quarter of 2025 through the first quarter of 2026 included same-store sales increases of 14.1%, 31.4%, 31.6%, 23.7%, and 21.4%, respectively.&nbsp;

Driven by its strong quarterly performance, Brinker raised its full-year fiscal 2026 guidance to reflect a stronger sales and profit outlook for Chili’s, inclusive of any negative impact from closures and reduced hours caused by Winter Storm Fern. Brinker estimates the storm’s impact to be approximately $20 million in reduced revenue.&nbsp;

Meanwhile, Chili’s sibling concept Maggiano’s experienced a same-store sales decline of 2.4% in Q2. Total revenues dropped by 14.5%, to $134.9 million, from $149.4 million in Q2 2025. Restaurant operating margin as a percentage of company sales declined 6.7% to 16%.&nbsp;

The company said it is focused on execution to improve performance and operations through its “Back to Maggiano’s” strategy, which includes initiatives across food, service, and atmosphere. Maggiano’s experienced a leadership transition in August, when &nbsp;Dominique Bertolone stepped down as president. Hochman has since assumed his duties and has been applying some of Chili’s turnaround playbook toward the concept.&nbsp;

